<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
The description is largely based on DAOM 220988 due to good development of conidiomata. However, we select DAOM 230637 as the holotype, because DNA data are only available for this specimen. Microscopic data of the two specimens are identical. This species is currently only known as an asexual morph. One specimen from Victoria (DAVFP 3092) contains also an immature sexual morph, which corresponds to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tul. &amp; C. Tul., Select. fung. carpol. (Paris) 2: 122" authorityYear="1863" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis alni" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="alni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis alni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
superficially. Barr apparently identified her collections as 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. marginalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="marginalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. marginalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because the latter was, at that time, considered to be the only alnicolous species occurring in North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Jensen, JD" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="275 - 281" refId="B21" refString="Jensen, JD, 1984. Melanconis marginalis from Northern Idaho. Mycotaxon 20: 275 - 281" title="Melanconis marginalis from Northern Idaho." volume="20" year="1984">Jensen 1984</bibRefCitation>
), which also occurs on 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. rubra" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">A. rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" author="Sieber, TN" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="2170 - 2176" refId="B39" refString="Sieber, TN, Sieber-Canavesi, F, Petrini, O, Ekramoddoullah, AKM, Dorworth, CE, 1991. Characterization of Canadian and European Melanconium from some Alnus species by morphological, cultural and biochemical studies. Canadian Journal of Botany 69: 2170 - 2176, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" title="Characterization of Canadian and European Melanconium from some Alnus species by morphological, cultural and biochemical studies." url="https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" volume="69" year="1991">Sieber et al. 1991</bibRefCitation>
). However, the conidia of the latter species are longer, more fusoid, have a larger l/w ratio and are lighter in colour than those of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. pacifica" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="α-conidia">α-conidia</normalizedToken>
of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. pacifica" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. alni" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. alni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are virtually identical in size. Those of the latter, however, have a different shape, a median light band and a more greyish-brown colour. Remarkably, 
<bibRefCitation author="Wehmeyer, LE" journalOrPublisher="University of Michigan Studies, Scientific Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 161" refId="B64" refString="Wehmeyer, LE, 1941. A Revision of Melanconis, Pseudovalsa, Prosthecium, and Titania. University of Michigan Studies, Scientific Series 14: 1 - 161" title="A Revision of Melanconis, Pseudovalsa, Prosthecium, and Titania." volume="14" year="1941">Wehmeyer (1941)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned a collection from the American Pacific region (Oregon) which had conidia resembling 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconium sphaeroideum" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="sphaeroideum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconium sphaeroideum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a synonym of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. alni" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. alni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" author="Sieber, TN" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="2170 - 2176" refId="B39" refString="Sieber, TN, Sieber-Canavesi, F, Petrini, O, Ekramoddoullah, AKM, Dorworth, CE, 1991. Characterization of Canadian and European Melanconium from some Alnus species by morphological, cultural and biochemical studies. Canadian Journal of Botany 69: 2170 - 2176, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" title="Characterization of Canadian and European Melanconium from some Alnus species by morphological, cultural and biochemical studies." url="https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" volume="69" year="1991">Sieber et al. (1991)</bibRefCitation>
included 10 isolates from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Alnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Alnus rubra" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Alnus rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sampled in British Columbia, that they identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Link" authorityYear="1825" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconium apiocarpum" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="apiocarpum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconium apiocarpum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, another synonym of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. alni" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. alni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above), based on conidial size and shape. Their measurements and, in particular, their illustration (fig. 2a) of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="α-conidia">α-conidia</normalizedToken>
fully agree with 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. pacifica" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The isozyme patterns of 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" author="Sieber, TN" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="2170 - 2176" refId="B39" refString="Sieber, TN, Sieber-Canavesi, F, Petrini, O, Ekramoddoullah, AKM, Dorworth, CE, 1991. Characterization of Canadian and European Melanconium from some Alnus species by morphological, cultural and biochemical studies. Canadian Journal of Botany 69: 2170 - 2176, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" title="Characterization of Canadian and European Melanconium from some Alnus species by morphological, cultural and biochemical studies." url="https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" volume="69" year="1991">Sieber et al. (1991)</bibRefCitation>
revealed high similarities, but also diagnostic differences between the isolates from European 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. glutinosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="glutinosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">A. glutinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and Canadian 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. rubra" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">A. rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is in agreement with the close phylogenetic relationship between 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. alni" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. alni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. pacifica" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Our morphological re-investigations of the isolates of 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" author="Sieber, TN" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="2170 - 2176" refId="B39" refString="Sieber, TN, Sieber-Canavesi, F, Petrini, O, Ekramoddoullah, AKM, Dorworth, CE, 1991. Characterization of Canadian and European Melanconium from some Alnus species by morphological, cultural and biochemical studies. Canadian Journal of Botany 69: 2170 - 2176, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" title="Characterization of Canadian and European Melanconium from some Alnus species by morphological, cultural and biochemical studies." url="https://doi.org/10.1139/b91-272" volume="69" year="1991">Sieber et al. (1991)</bibRefCitation>
, which are kept as dried cultures at DAVFP (see specimens cited above), confirmed that they represent 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. pacifica" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
In DAOM, two additional specimens, labelled 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wehm., Pap. Michigan Acad. I. 6: 382" authorityYear="1926" baseAuthorityName="Peck" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconis marginalis" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="marginalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Melanconis marginalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected by Barr in the same area, are extant, DAOM 227727 and DAOM 227345. These specimens, however, do not contain 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. pacifica" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">M. pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the sexual morph of a 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nitschke &amp; Pyrenomyc.Germ" authorityYear="1870" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Diaporthaceae" genus="Diaporthe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Diaporthe" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Diaporthe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp.
</paragraph>
